European inflation slipped in food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the vertiginous increase in food prices.
Price increases in November have been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, recording - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Luxembourg-based Union Statistical Office.
Official forecasts were only as likely as 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the U.S., British and Canadian issuer banks, did not cut basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with rising commodity prices and the reduction in forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to 2 percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the trap 22: "negotiating" about inflation so that it later does not have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 per cent, recorded in Germany, broke the record for twelve years, while in Spain it increased from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation sparked in the euro area as a result of sluggish food and energy prices.
Wheat-to-grain quotas increased by 88 percent, and soybean quotas reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007, much more had to be paid for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market rose by 52 percent this year, reaching black gold almost <0x24>100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from 2.1 per cent current to 2.5 per cent, while for 2009 it will drop already to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain around 3 percent in the next 3 or 4 months, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to double interest rates during 2008.
