In many hospitals it saves with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been reported in hospitals, first of all due to the improper use of antibiotics.
The prevailing hygiene conditions in hospitals, bed bumps and staff overload do not favor infection control, says the head of the department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it saves even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, an MRSA infection has been diagnosed in the traumatology department of János Hospital.
The presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected in a hospitalized man after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
A wounded from a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the patient himself soon afterwards had to return to the hospital as a result of the MRSA infection and since then no major surgical intervention has been possible due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10 this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National System of Nosocomialis Surveillance, said Karolina Böröcz, head of the department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has been safely recorded in hospitals, otherwise no information is available.
Nearly two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
A third of humans carry the bacteria Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their noses without causing any disease.
SA-produced infections (e.g. throat inflammation, amygdalite, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is applied excessively or improperly to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics turn into highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria and quickly infect with inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, for example wound infections or septicemia first in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, patients with weakened organisms, the elderly, or people with low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, the MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic-resistant
“These patients are isolated, nursing staff cares for them in rubber gloves and masks, and there are suitable antibiotics for their treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are examined beforehand to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but even so infection can not be prevented in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital MRSA infections in most cases, however current national hospital conditions do not favor the prevention of formation and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection mainly occurs in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA in their body.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Box does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases go out to the public when already visible MRSA infections occur in the patient - said the doctor-in-chief of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict recommendations for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives for treating infections and pathological frameworks.
Antibiotic therapy should be directed, that is, microbiological tests should be done to prevent resistance to drugs, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological samples are even less frequent in the case of ambulance patients or in basic care, Karolina Börocz said.
Save with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is transmitted from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also considerable shortcomings in hospitals in this regard.
MRSA is contagious through droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however, in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, the hospital rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very joint, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least 1.5 meters away.
Unfortunately, it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in less favourable economic situation hospitals is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a higher likelihood of infection.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate preventive measures are followed, fewer infections of this type are reported or the pathogen infection can be stopped.
Government Programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is being fought in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
The program appears to be successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a downward trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) prioritises the prevention of multiresistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
