The party is not always written with red numbers.
In Hungary, the law accurately defines the days that are written with red numbers on the calendar and has already become a widespread practice that around the holidays - which the next year will be less - workdays are reorganized.
Even in the EU or North America, the holidays are not uniform.
Hungarian laws make a difference between national holiday, state holiday and festive days.
The festive days are mainly related to religious festivals and historical ephemerals.
We also celebrate the New Year: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is festive - this last one especially so that those who spent celebrating the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven festivities written with red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on March 15 in memory of the revolution of 1848 and on October 23, commemorative day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20 we celebrate the foundation of the State, on May 1 the feast of work, on November 1 and 2 we remember our deceased family and friends.
In addition, in our country there are two-day celebrations of the Passover of Resurrection, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, which is why it is often done bridge when before or after the holiday there is only one working day.
In exchange for such extended weekends, during previous Saturdays you cannot be absent from work or school.
It is the Minister of Labour who regulates in his specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day directly before or after the party.
This legal norm is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and public officials.
It is not mandatory in return for companies and services institutions that, because of their function, work continuously even during holidays.
This year the order of work can only be altered around the holidays of the end of the year: from December 24, life practically stops in the country, as according to experiences, most people "do bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
Next year several of our holidays will coincide with mid or weekends, so there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
First, the agenda around the work party will be modified so that then, for four consecutive days, workers can rest.
On Saturday, April 26, it will be a working day, so that Friday, May 2 will be a festive day.
The other change relates to the October 23rd party: on Saturday 18th October, you will have to work instead of Friday 24th.
Instead, the year that comes during the end-of-year holiday will be able to rest, as from December 24 it will not work almost anywhere, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
