A Heavy Memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, describing the fate of the 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of archives, stored over 27 km of shelves to Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not so far consultable only for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is, individually and nominally, at the request of a former victim or its right-holders.
The eleven states in charge of its management – such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May 2006 to open them to seekers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening is effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow searches "particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, director of these files managed by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, objected to the opening to the public of these nominative documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or the mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or the detention orders established by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find the deported or subject to compulsory labour and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their detention, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin, said in 2006.
