Venus: Earth's twin brother.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that had not yet been posed. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls in the poles, the same ones that appear also in winter on Earth.
For the past three decades, researchers had suspected that rays could exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new tests: it has discovered electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, the rays shut down at a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to Urey-Miller’s famous model of the origin of life, rays caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it is not so: if there was life there one day, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface there are temperatures of 500<0xC2><0xB0>C, oscillating in such a way that temperatures can be reached below zero.
"Possibly, Venus is a "diabolic" twin on Earth, but it's still a twin," Russell said.
The main objective of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth by its mass and size, has evolved so differently.
Since there have been no special missions since the 1990s, only for the exploration of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for the exploration of Venus.
The latest findings of the research that will be presented in many "Nature" articles, according to the researchers, not only underscore the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
“This also demonstrates that neighboring planets have more features in common with Earth than we had assumed,” the ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers have discovered in the southern polar region also a vortex formed by clouds that rotate faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high atmospheric layers of the poles, according to a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has almost the same mass as Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet is also called an dawn star or evening star orbiting the Sun almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: a day on Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars is not very similar to Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On both planets there had been a lot of water left on Earth in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated into the universe.
While carbon dioxide had become carbon stones on Earth, Venus forms most of the atmosphere.
